R-Packages for Gaussian Process Regression

Afra Kilic, Supervisor: dr. ir. Joris Mulder

2023-03-31

Gaussian Process (GP) regression and Generalized Additive Models (GAMs) are both popular methods used in statistical modeling and machine learning for regression tasks. This work aims to compare available R packages to fit GP regression with each other and also with GAM. In the first part, the following R functions will be compared in terms of computation time, quantification of degree of non-linearity, posterior uncertainty and testing multiple predictors (i.e., multiple \(X_{i}\));

  • gam from "mgcv"
  • brm from "brms"
  • cvek from "CVEK"
  • gpr from "GPFDA"
  • gausspr from "kernlab"
  • GauPro from "GauPro"

The more detailed information regarding each package can be found in the package documentations, this work is only focused on the GP regression function in each package.

In the second part, a real data example will be presented to compare GP regression with GAM and GLM by testing the hypothesis “the sharing of fake news is largely driven by low conscientiousness conservatives” from the study by Lawson and Kakkar (2021).

Generalized Additive Models (GAMs)

GAMs are a type of regression model that allow for flexible, non-linear relationships between the predictor variables and the response variable. GAMs accomplish this by modeling the response variable as a sum of smooth functions of the predictor variables, rather than a linear combination. This allows for more complex and nuanced relationships to be captured, which can be particularly useful when the true relationship between variables is not well understood or linear.

A generalized additive model for a response variable \(Y\), modeled as a function of predictor variables \(X_{1}, X_{2}, ..., X_{n}\) can be expressed as:

\[ g(E(Y)) = \beta_{0} + f_{1}(X_{1}) + f_{2}(X_{2}) + ... + f_{p}(X_{n}) + \epsilon \] where \(f_{i}\) are smooth, non-linear functions of the predictor variables \(X_{i}\), and \(\epsilon\) is a random error term. The functions \(f_{i}\) can be modeled using a variety of smoothing methods, such as splines, kernel methods, or generalized cross-validation.

Gaussian Process (GP) Regression

On the other hand, Gaussian Process regression is a probabilistic regression model that is based on the assumption that the response variable follows a Gaussian distribution. GP regression can be seen as a generalization of linear regression, as it allows for non-linear relationships between the predictor variables and the response variable as well. However, rather than modeling the response variable as a sum of smooth functions of the predictor variables, GP regression models the response variable as a distribution over functions. This allows for greater flexibility in modeling complex relationships and also provides a measure of uncertainty in the predictions. The regression function modeled by a multivariate Guassian can be expressed as:

\[ P(f|X) = N(f|\mu, K) \]

where \(X=[x_{1}, ..., x_{n}], f =[f(x_{1}), ..., f(x_{n})], \mu = [m(x_{1}, ..., m(x_{n}))]\), and \(K_{ij} = k(x_{i}, x_{j})\). \(X\) are observed data points, \(m\) represents the mean function, and \(k\) represent a positive definite kernel function, which is Radial Basis Function Kernel in this work. Notice that with no observation, the mean function is default to be \(m(X) = 0\) given that the data is often normalized to a zero mean. The GP model is a distribution over functions and \(K\) defines the shape (smoothness) of this distribution. In particular, if the points \(x_{i}\) and \(x_{j}\) are considered similar by the kernel, then the function outputs of them, \(f(x_{i})\) and \(f(x_{j})\) are expected to be similar. RBF kernel can be expressed as:

\[ k(x_{i}, x_{j}) = exp(- \frac{||x_{i}, x_{j}||^2} {2l^2}) \] where \(l\) is a free positive parameter, also called \(length\) parameter. Higher values of \(l\) leads to smoother curves whereas lower values leads to more wiggly curves.

One of the key differences between GAMs and GP regression is their underlying assumptions about the nature of the relationships between variables. GAMs assume that the relationships are smooth and can be represented by a sum of smooth functions, while GP regression assumes that the relationships are continuous and can be represented by a distribution over functions. Additionally, GAMs are typically simpler to implement and interpret, while GP regression can be computationally intensive and requires more expertise to use effectively. Ultimately, the choice between GAMs and GP regression will depend on the specific nature of the data and the modeling task at hand.

Part-I: Package Summaries & One-Predictor Model Application

In this part, the summary of each package will be given and the function of interest of each package will be used to fit the following model with non-linear relation between one-predictor and the outcome;

\[ y = 0.5\frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-\frac{1}{2}(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma})^{2}} \times x + \epsilon, \qquad \epsilon \sim {\sf N}(0, 0.1) \] First, the required packages have to be loaded. You can access to the overview of the packages on CRAN.

library(mgcv)
library(brms)
library(kernlab)
library(GPFDA)
library(CVEK)
library(gam)
library(GauPro)

Data Generation


#Data Generation
set.seed(123)
n <- 250
xobs <- sort(runif(n,min=-3,max=3))
mu = rep(0,length(xobs))
sigma2 <- .1**2
error <- rnorm(n,sd=sqrt(sigma2))
yobs <- .5*dnorm(xobs)*xobs + error
data = as.data.frame(cbind(yobs, xobs))

#splitting into train and test data 
sample <- sample(c(TRUE, FALSE), nrow(data), replace=TRUE, prob=c(0.8,0.2))
train <- data[sample,]
test <- data[!sample,]
#LM fit 

start_time_lm1 <- Sys.time()
fit_lm1 <- lm(yobs~ xobs, data = train)
end_time_lm1 <- Sys.time()
computation_time_lm1 <- end_time_lm1 - start_time_lm1
cat("Computation time LM:", computation_time_lm1, "minutes")

  • The model of interest shows a positive monotonic relationship between \(x\) and \(y\), so lm identifies a significant positive effect of \(x\) on \(y\). However, looking at the plots, it cannot capture the non-linear trend between the variables, which increases error rate.

mgcv

The function of interest, gam, fits generalized additive models, including quadratically penalized GLMs and other models estimated by a quadratically penalized likelihood approach. The smoothness of model terms is estimated during fitting (e.g. using AIC/BIC), and confidence/credible intervals are available for any predicted quantity. Smooth terms are represented using penalized regression splines or similar smoothers, and multi-dimensional smooths are available using penalized thin plate regression splines or tensor product splines. Linear functionals of smooths can also be included in models.

start_time_gam1 <- Sys.time()
fit_gam1 <- mgcv::gam(yobs~ s(xobs), family='gaussian')
end_time_gam1 <- Sys.time()
computation_time_gam1 <- end_time_gam1 - start_time_gam1
cat("Computation time GAM:", computation_time_gam1, "minutes")

legend(-2, 0.3, legend=c("Actual", "Predictions"), col = c("blue", "red"), lty=1:2, cex=0.8)

  • The output is separated into parametric and smooth (i.e. non-parametric) parts. In this case, the only parametric component is the intercept as we added smooth term to \(x\) variable. For both estimate types, the output includes p-value. Normally, degrees of freedom refers is equal to the number of features/terms in the model. However, p-values for smooth terms are based on effective degrees of freedom (edf). As in typical OLS, we are still trying to minimize the residual sums of squares, but in this case penalty for “wiggliness” have to be taken into consideration. So, the default p-value for the smooth term test is based on edf and the rank \(r\) of the covariance matrix for the coefficients for a particular smooth. Conceptually, p-value is associated with the \(F(r, n - edf)\). We cannot evaluate the p-values for smooth terms straightforwardly as in the parametric component (i.e., \(p < 0.05\)). But, it is still assumed that if the p-value for a smooth terms is very close to zero, then it may be concluded that there is a significant effect of the predictor on the outcome.

  • The edf is a summary statistic of GAM and it reﬂects the degree of non-linearity of a curve (Wood 2006). An edf equal to 1 is equivalent to a linear relationship, 1 < edf ≤ 2 is considered a weakly non- linear relationship, and edf > 2 implies a highly non- linear relationship (Stenseth et al. 2006, Litzow and Ciannelli 2007, Zuur et al. 2009). As the edf increasingly exceeds 2, the degree of non- linearity progressively increases. In this case, edf is \(5.9\) meaning that the relationship between \(x\) and \(y\) is highly non-linear.

  • Another important metric in GAM output is generalized cross validation (GCV) score, an estimation of the mean square prediction error obtained through a leave-one-out cross validation process. This involves fitting the model to all observations except one, and then calculating the squared residual for predicting that omitted observation using the model. This process is repeated for all observations. However, the GCV score efficiently measures this concept without the need to fit all those models, and it also overcomes other issues. By default, the GCV score is minimized to determine the smooth’s specific nature. While the GCV score alone doesn’t provide much information, it can be used as a comparative measure similar to AIC for choosing among different models, with lower scores being preferable.

  • Information on posterior uncertainty quantification for the model itself is also provided in the gam object. However, it does not provide uncertainty information for the predicted values.

brms

The function of interest brm fits Bayesian generalized (non-)linear multivariate multilevel models using Stan for full Bayesian inference. It supports a wide range of distributions and link functions, including linear, robust linear, count data, survival, response times, ordinal, zero-inflated, hurdle, and self-defined mixture models in a multilevel context. Other modeling options include non-linear and smooth terms, auto-correlation structures, censored data, and meta-analytic standard errors. Prior specifications are flexible and model fit can be assessed and compared using posterior predictive checks and leave-one-out cross-validation.

set.seed(123)
start_time_brms1 <- Sys.time()
fit_brms1 <- brms::brm(yobs ~ gp(xobs), data = train, chains = 2)

  • In general, every parameter is summarized using the mean (Estimate) and the standard deviation (Est.Error) of the posterior distribution as well as two-sided 95% credible intervals (l-95% CI and u-95% CI) based on quantiles. If the parameter estimates are not in the 95% CI interval, then we can say that the evidence based on the data and applied model is not very strong and still insufficient by standard decision rules. In this case, every parameter estimate is located within the 95% CI interval. However, we should also check the last three values (ESS_bulk,ESS_tail, and Rhat) which provide information on how well the algorithm could estimate the posterior distribution of this parameter. If Rhat is considerably greater than 1, the algorithm has not yet converged and it is necessary to run more iterations and / or set stronger priors. In this case, Rhat is greater than 1, so the model did not converge. Thus, it is necessary to run more iterations or set stronger priors to achieve convergence.

  • This package only support the exponentiated-quadratic kernel which is defines as \(k(x_{i}, x_{j}) = sdgp^{2}exp(-||x_{i}-x_{j}||^{2}/(2lscale^{2}))\), where \(||.||\) is Euclidean norm, \(sdgp\) is a standard deviation parameter, and \(lscale\) is the length scale parameter. brm object gives the parameter estimates in the “Gaussian Process Terms” section with 95CI. lscale estimates refers to “wiggliness” of the relationship so it can be considered as the quantification of degree of non-linearity.

To investigate and compare model fit, we can apply graphical posterior predictive checks, which make use of the bayesplot package on the backend.

brms::pp_check(fit_brms1)
#> Using 10 posterior draws for ppc type 'dens_overlay' by default.

CVEK

The function of interest cvek allows us to model joint nonlinear effect of multiple covariates. It provides hypothesis tests for main effects and interactions among features based on ensemble learning with kernel-ridge estimators. Hypothesis testing uses either the asymptotic or the bootstrap version of a generalized score test. The latter method allows us to deal with small sample sizes. The package offers a range of choices for kernel family, model selection criteria, ensembling method, and type of hypothesis test, making it a flexible and easy-to-use implementation of CVEK.

See this document for the details of the hypothesis testing procedure using cvek.

set.seed(123)
kern_par <- data.frame(method = c("linear", "rbf"), #model library specification
                       l = rep(1, 2), p = 1:2, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
# define kernel library
kern_func_list <- CVEK::define_library(kern_par)

start_time_cvek1 <- Sys.time()
fit_CVEK1 <- CVEK::cvek(yobs ~  k(xobs) , kern_func_list = kern_func_list, data = train, 
                       lambda = exp(seq(-3, 5)), test = "asymp")   
end_time_cvek1 <- Sys.time()
computation_time_cvek1 <- end_time_cvek1 - start_time_cvek1 
cat("Computation time CVEK:", computation_time_cvek1, "minutes")
#> Computation time CVEK: 5.65214 minutes

fit_CVEK1$beta #Fixed effect estimate of x on y.
#>              [,1]
#> [1,] -0.002954157
fit_CVEK1$lambda #The selected tuning parameter based on the estimated ensemble kernel matrix.
#> [1] 0.04978707
fit_CVEK1$u_hat #A vector of weights of the kernels in the library.
#> [1] 0 1

#Testing the model 
pred_CVEK1 <- predict(fit_CVEK1, newdata = test)

plot(test$xobs, test$yobs, main = "Actual Observations vs. Predictons", 
     xlab = "x", ylab = "y", col = "blue", pch = 19)
points(test$xobs, pred_CVEK1, col = "red", type = "b")
legend(-2, 0.3, legend=c("Actual", "Predictions"), col = c("blue", "red"), lty=1:2, cex=0.8)

  • \(k()\) is specified as semi-parametric model with a model library including linear and rbf kernels with l=1. here, we include the non-linearity to the model with the rbf kernel. fit_CVEK1$u_hat shows us that the ensemble weight assigns 1 to the rbf kernel, meaning that the relationship between \(x\) and \(y\) is not linear.

  • fit_CVEK1$beta shows the fixed effect estimates of the predictor on the outcome variable. In this case, the fixed effect of \(x\) is estimated as a non-positive value. But the model also says that the relationship is not linear, so it is not very easy to comment on these estimates directly. Hypothesis testing procedure can be applied.

  • fit_CVEK1$lambda refers to the selected tuning parameter based on the estimated kernel matrix. When fit_CVEK1$lambda equals to zero, then there is no penalty to the model which may refer that the relationship is linear. So this metric can also be seen as a quantification of non-linearity.

  • However, posterior uncertainty quantification is a little bit unclear in this package.

GPFDA

This package is for modelling functional data with multidimensional inputs, multivariate functional data, and non-separable and/or non-stationary covariance structure of function-valued processes. The function of interest gpr fits GP regression for a single or multiple independent outcomes.

  • We specify the covariance matrix for gpr functin as Cov = matern. It has another positive parameter called \(\nu\) besides on the length parameter \(\sigma\) in rbf kernel. As goes to infinity, Matern covariance matrix converges to squared exponential covariance matrix. (see this for more detail).
start_time_gpr1 <- Sys.time()

  • gpr function estimates the hyperparameters of the covariance matrix. So it returns two hyperparameter estimation as matern.w and matern.v in log scale. vv stands for Gaussian white noise. You can also see the variance of the paramater estimates. For matern covariance matrix, it is not clear in the package documentation which parameter estimation to which parameter of matern covariance matrix. \(\rho\) parameter of matern covariance matrix shows the smoothness and it is very similar to \(l\) parameter of rbf. So this function normally quantifies the non-linearity but it is not clear in the matern case.

  • Information on posterior uncertainty quantification is also provided in the gpr object.

  • gausspr object returns “training error” and the relevant hyperparameter estimate of the model. In our case it is \(l\) parameter of RBF kernel which defines the smoothness of the distribution. As \(l\) parameter defines smoothness of the relationship, this function also quantifies the degree of non-linearity.

  • We can also calculate the mean and the covariance matrix by using estimation to calculate the CI95 manually as following;

x_predict <- seq(-5,5,len=50)

#Radial Basis Kernel 
SE <- function(Xi,Xj, l=1) exp(-0.5 * (Xi - Xj) ^ 2 / l ^ 2)
cov <- function(X, Y) outer(X, Y, SE)

#Mean and Covariance Matrix
sigma <- fit_gausspr1@kernelf@kpar[[1]] #sigma estimated by the model 
cov_xx_inv <- solve(cov(train$xobs, train$xobs) + sigma^2 * diag(1, length(train$xobs)))
Ef <- cov(x_predict, train$xobs) %*% cov_xx_inv %*% train$yobs
Cf <- cov(x_predict, x_predict) - cov(x_predict, train$xobs)  %*% cov_xx_inv %*% cov(train$xobs, x_predict)

Part-II: Real Data Example

In this part, I will test the hypothesis from the study by Lawson and Kakkar (2021): “the sharing of fake news is largely driven by low conscientiousness conservatives”. The original study tested this hypothesis using linear fit, following that Simonsohn (2022) tested the same hypothesis with gam fit to illustrate the similarities and differences between linear and GAM simple slopes. The original data and the code is accessible here. use this code: OVTJGP .

I will also fit the same model using glm, gam, and brm to illustrate how gaussian process regression differs from gam and glm.

The out outcome variable of the model of interest is categorical (i.e., 1 = sharing & 0 = not sharing), so the task is a classifcation task with a sample size of 23,928. Among all packages, there are two packages with gp classification: brm and gausspr. While brm is computationally more inefficient at relatively small sample sizes like in the simulation study in part-I, it is way more efficient than gausspr at large sample sizes. For this reason, brm function is determined to be used in real data example.

#Low vs high moderator
sdk=1
xpredict=1:7
z.low  <- mean(data$c) - sd(data$c)*sdk
z.high <- mean(data$c) + sd(data$c)*sdk

Bootstrap for both glm and gam simple slopes

#Unique participant id to bootstrap by it
data <- subset(data, non_US_ip==0)
# Function for quantiles to run through apply
    q025 <- function(x) quantile(x,.025)
    q975 <- function(x) quantile(x,.975)

  #Automatically name elements in list with name of the objects in the list
    #https://stackoverflow.com/questions/16951080/can-lists-be-created-that-name-themselves-based-on-input-object-names
    namedList <- function(...) {
      L <- list(...)
      snm <- sapply(substitute(list(...)),deparse)[-1]
      if (is.null(nm <- names(L))) nm <- snm
      if (any(nonames <- nm=="")) nm[nonames] <- snm[nonames]
      setNames(L,nm)
    }
    
  # BOTH (gam and lm) simple slopes for the bootstrap study
      both.simple.slope <- function(x,z,y,sdk=1,xpredict=1:7)
      {
      #Estimate gam model
       # g <- gam(y~s(x,k=4)+s(z,k=4)+ti(x,z),family='binomial')
        g <- mgcv::gam(y~te(x,z),family='binomial')
        m <- glm(y~x*z,family='binomial')

      #Low vs high moderator
        z.low  <- mean(z) - sd(z)*sdk
        z.high <- mean(z) + sd(z)*sdk
      
      #gam.Spotlight  
        gam.y.high <-predict(g , newdata = data.frame(z=z.high,x=xpredict),type='response')
        gam.y.low  <-predict(g , newdata = data.frame(z=z.low,x=xpredict), type='response')
        
      #probit (it's actually logit, legacy comments and variable names)
         probit.y.high <-predict(m , newdata = data.frame(z=z.high,x=xpredict),type='response')
         probit.y.low  <-predict(m , newdata = data.frame(z=z.low,x=xpredict), type='response')
      
        
        return(namedList(gam.y.high , gam.y.low, probit.y.high, probit.y.low))
      }
      
 # Bootstrap study  

      set.seed(50)
      
    #Unique participant id to bootstrap by it
      participant.all <- unique(data$participant)
      
    #Smaller dataset with just the 3 variables of interest
      data.subset <- subset(data,select=c("share", "participant","c","conservatism"))
      
    #How many bootstraps
      btot=250
      
    #Empty tables with results from bootstrap
      gam.y.high.boot = gam.y.low.boot = 
      probit.y.high.boot = probit.y.low.boot = 
      matrix(nrow=btot,ncol=7)                  #empty matrix
    
    #Bootstrap loop
      for (bk in 1:btot){
        
      #Initiate empty dataframe
        data.boot <-data.frame(share=c(),c=c(),conservatism=c())
        
      #Draw participants IDs for this bootstrap
        participant.boot <- sample(participant.all,replace=TRUE)
        
      #Get their data
        for (k in 1:length(participant.boot)) {
          data.boot <-rbind(data.boot, subset(data.subset , participant==participant.boot[k]))
        }
      
      #
        s.boot <- both.simple.slope(x=data.boot$conservatism, z=data.boot$c, y=data.boot$share)
        gam.y.high.boot[bk,] <- s.boot$gam.y.high
        gam.y.low.boot[bk,] <- s.boot$gam.y.low
        probit.y.high.boot[bk,] <- s.boot$probit.y.high
        probit.y.low.boot[bk,] <- s.boot$probit.y.low
        cat("...",bk)
    }

      bootstrap.results<-namedList(gam.y.high.boot,    gam.y.low.boot, 
                                   probit.y.high.boot, probit.y.low.boot)
      
      
      
    #Compute 2.5th and 97.5th percentils
      # GAM
        yh1.g.lb <- apply(bootstrap.results$gam.y.high.boot,2,q025)
        yh1.g.ub <- apply(bootstrap.results$gam.y.high.boot,2,q975)
        yh0.g.lb <- apply(bootstrap.results$gam.y.low.boot,2,q025)
        yh0.g.ub <- apply(bootstrap.results$gam.y.low.boot,2,q975)
      
      #Logit
        yh1.m.lb <- apply(bootstrap.results$probit.y.high.boot,2,q025)
        yh1.m.ub <- apply(bootstrap.results$probit.y.high.boot,2,q975)
        yh0.m.lb <- apply(bootstrap.results$probit.y.low.boot,2,q025)
        yh0.m.ub <- apply(bootstrap.results$probit.y.low.boot,2,q975)
      
#Combine into single vector
      #GAM CI
        ci1.g <- c(yh1.g.ub, rev(yh1.g.lb))  #Confidence interval for high moderator
        ci0.g <- c(yh0.g.ub, rev(yh0.g.lb))  #Confidence interval for low  moderator
      
        
      #LOGIT  CI
        ci1.m <- c(yh1.m.ub, rev(yh1.m.lb))
        ci0.m <- c(yh0.m.ub, rev(yh0.m.lb))

Plots for glm and gam

Simonsohn shows how gam performs better at showing the non-linear interaction between conscientiousness and being conservative. As we can notice from the GAM simple slopes; On average less conscientious people are more likely to share fake news but conservatism increases this effect more than the glm graph shows. Also notice the inflection point in the high conscientiousness line (in red) in GAM simple slopes graph. In particular, if a person is neither liberal nor conservative, regardless of their conscientiousness level they tend to share fake news more or less in the same level. In sum, Simonsohn argues that the models allowing us to observe non-linear relationships can be better because social phenomenons can be non-linear despite we commonly expect them to be linear.

Plot for brm

  • As lscale shows, the interaction does not seem linear. brm also estimated that low conscientious people tend to share more fake news but confidence intervals are totally overlapped, meaning that there is no really a difference. It also shows that there the conservatism’s moderation effect is not linear. Interestingly, people score 5 at conservatism scale tend to share more fake news based the GP simple slopes.
